“They may take our lives, but they will never take, our FREEDOM” <br>
<br>
William Wallace <br>
<br>
Scottish Patriot <br>
<br>
Earth Year 1297 A.D. <br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Chapter 1: Mail Call <br>
<br>
The Andromeda was docked with Haukin Tao Drift – no matter where they went the crew always seemed to end up back at that drift. Dylan, Rommie and Harper had stayed on board while Beka, Trance and Tyr went shopping. For once the Andromeda was in tiptop shape and had a full supply of spare parts. While things were quiet Dylan took the liberty of downloading the mail waiting for his small crew. While he was sorting the flexi’s in to piles for their respective recipients something about one of Harper’s messages caught his attention – the name of the sender: Brendan. <br>
<br>
Dylan never clicked right away but after several seconds of staring at the flexi he realised what the message meant. Quickly he grabbed the flexi and headed out of command. <br>
<br>
“Andromeda, where’s Harper?” <br>
<br>
“He’s just entered machine shop 17.” Replied the disembodied voice of the ship made flesh. “Shall I tell him you’re looking for him?” <br>
<br>
“No, no, don’t do anything.” <br>
<br>
Dylan quickly made his way through the ships many corridors to Harper’s machine shop and arrived minutes later, ‘Huh, new record’ he thought to himself. <br>
<br>
When Dylan entered the machine shop Harper was busy looking for something. <br>
<br>
“What have you lost?” He said while slightly out of breath. <br>
<br>
“My nano-welder.” Harper was clearly frustrated. “Where’s Trance when you need her.” <br>
<br>
Dylan looked around and saw it lying on the floor behind a trolley. He picked it up and handed it to Harper. <br>
<br>
“Thanks, sure you’re not Trance in disguise?” <br>
<br>
“Nope, but I bet I can brighten your day.” He handed Harper the flexi. Just as he sat down to read, Andromeda informed Dylan of an incoming message for him – from Charlemagne Bolivar. <br>
<br>
“Captain Hunt.” <br>
<br>
“Charlemagne Bolivar, how can I help you?” <br>
<br>
“Actually, it’s how I can help you.” <br>
<br>
“Care to elaborate on that.” <br>
<br>
For the next few minutes Charlemagne explained himself telling Dylan that the Drago Kazov have developed some kind of new weapon and were planning to turn it against the new Commonwealth now fifty-two worlds strong. He told him of a missile – partially sentient and programmed to reach it’s target no matter what – that it had stealth capability, an AI system and a limited point defence system. He also told of the Dragon’s plans to use it against the member worlds and the new High Guard fleet being built at San-Ska-Rae. However, what shocked Dylan the most was where the missile was being developed - on Earth. <br>
<br>
Dylan saw the chance to kill two birds with one stone and make the best of a bad situation. He could keep his promise to Harper and deal a devastating blow to the Drago Kazov. Under the terms of The Mutual Defence Pact the Sabre-Jaguar fleet would aid in the defence of the member worlds until the threat was taken care of. Dylan had his own fleet to take care of the Drago Kazov in the Sol system. <br>
<br>
Their discussion took about ten minutes during which Harper had read and reread the message countless times, he couldn’t believe it, all this time he had thought Brendan was dead, now he had hope. Once Dylan had finished he looked at Harper. <br>
<br>
“Save it, you don’t have to ask, we’re going to Earth.” <br>
<br>
Harper was overjoyed but Dylan was horrified. Such a weapon would spell destruction for the fragile alliance of the new Commonwealth. <br>
<br>
“Rommie, recall Tyr, Beka and Trance, we’re leaving.” <br>
<br>
“Eye sir.” The screen persona of the ship replied. <br>
<br>
With that Dylan left for command to start planning his latest quest, luckily for him, as the Captain of the flagship of the Commonwealth and principle recruiter, he had some leeway when it came to the ruling council and their orders. <br>
<br>
Harper sat on his bunk, shock still over running his bodily functions, he still couldn’t believe Brendan was alive, he was, entranced. Suddenly he realised he was alone and darted about trying to make himself presentable. He scurried around picking up his tools but stopped when he hit a snag. <br>
<br>
“Hey Andromeda, have you seen my forcelance.” <br>
<br>
“Harper, that’s disgusting.” <br>
<br>
“What?…No, no my actual forcelance, I can’t find it.” <br>
<br>
Andromeda’s hologram appeared, glancing at Harper. She closed her eyes briefly to scan the room. <br>
<br>
“It’s on your bunk in the corner, under your blue shirt.” <br>
<br>
“Thanks babe, you’re a lifesaver.” <br>
<br>
“Actually, I’m a warship, but close enough.” Harper smiled at her last comment as he picked up the lance and headed to command. <br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Chapter 2: preparations <br>
<br>
In command, once everyone was present, Dylan explained the situation and Andromeda replayed sections of the conversation between Dylan and Charlemagne dealing with the weapon. When he was done the crew stood in silence for several moments. <br>
<br>
“If that’s true, there will be no stopping the Drago Kazov and not even Drago Musevini’s remains will keep your ship intact.” Tyr said softly as he leaned against the bulkhead. Suddenly Dylan began to bark out orders. <br>
<br>
“Alright, Beka, Tyr, on the flight deck are two slip fighters being prepared for launch. Tyr, you’re going to Mobius. The high guard training facility should have a full battalion of lancers ready to go. Beka, Sintii, there should be a whole lot of engineer’s, officers, medic’s etcetera etcetera ready to go. Get them prepared to travel ASAP; we’ll meet Beka at Sintii in six hours. Tyr, we’ll rendezvous with you six hours later. The Drago Kazov want a war, we’ll give ‘em one.” <br>
<br>
They didn’t move, or rather they couldn’t. They couldn’t believe what Dylan had just said, since when was he ‘Mr. kick ass first, ask questions later’. With Beka and Tyr gone Dylan took the helm and streamed to the crab nebula, at the centre of which sat a hidden star system: simply a rogue star and a single planet, the perfect hiding place for the high guard fleet led by the wrath of Achilles. Ryan instantly hailed the Andromeda. <br>
<br>
“Captain hunt? Can I help you?” <br>
<br>
“Absolutely Ryan, I’m calling your fleet in to service. We’re starting a war.” <br>
<br>
“Terrific. I mean, well, you know, we’ve needed something to do. just tell us where and when.” <br>
<br>
“I thought you might say that. Andromeda, link up with the Achilles and the fleets NAV systems, we’ll be taking them with us. Harper, make sure the fleet is battle ready, trance, make sure they’re fully loaded with medical supplies, something tells me they’ll be needed.” <br>
<br>
with that they broke up and went about their business and prepared the fleet for battle. once the fleet was ready, Dylan had them fall into battle group formation with the Andromeda and the Achilles forming the centres of the two groups. with everyone ready the battle groups jumped in to the slipstream and headed to the rendezvous with Beka. <br>
<br>
The fleet emerged in Sintii space several minutes later to find Beka waiting in orbit leading a fleet of troop transports filled to the brim with officers, engineers, gunners, pilots, medics, and almost every other person required for Starship operations on board. Dylan was amazed at just how many people he had before him, never in his career had he ever had so many under his command. It took several hours to get the new crews split between the fleet and acclimated to their new environments and comfortable with their roles aboard ship. Once Dylan felt they were ready he decided it was time to meet up with Tyr, who by now was probably ready to kill most of the lancers he had met. <br>
<br>
With the flash of blue light the slipstream opened up and swallowed the fleet one by one, all now under the control of their own individual pilots. Minutes later they all returned to normal space on approach to Mobius and the waiting Lancers, Dylan’s fighting force and the means by which he would keep his promise to Harper and strike a deadly blow to the Dragans. When the Andromeda closed to real time viewing range Dylan and Rommie were amazed at the poetry before them, hundreds of ships, large, small and all full of Lancers. Seconds after the Andromeda streamed in a fleet of Nietzschean ships slipped in at their backs, luckily, they were Sabre-Jaguar taking their role seriously. <br>
<br>
Quickly, the Nietzscheans took up positions in orbit of Mobius ready to defend it at the first sign of trouble. The lancers easily found their new homes and adapted to them in less than an hour, everything was ready; well, almost everything. All that was left to do now was organise the forces on Earth. And, prove that Dylan kept his promises. Dylan decided the best staging area for the fleet would be in the Proxima Centari system. Despite being Sol systems next-door neighbour, the Dragans had no interest in the system so was perfect for Dylan’s needs. <br>
<br>
Dylan, Rommie and Harper took the Maru and slipped to Earth, but not before making sure the crews knew that the ships Avatar’s were in command, they did after all have much more experience than any other officer in history. Once again Rommie generated a false meteor storm to conceal the Maru’s landing and Harper led the way through the old streets of Boston to his cousin’s hide out. As they rounded the corner to the secret entrance the trio froze at the sound of multiple blasters charging. Fearing for their lives they thought better than trying to fight, they all knew how tough and relentless the Nietzscheans were but only Harper knew just how bad the particular Niets of Earth were and it showed in his body language despite the fact that he was standing still. <br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Chapter 3: An Old Acquaintance <br>
<br>
The small group stood absolutely still, well they tried to; Harper was reliving his child hood once again and he could barely do anything other than mutter to himself in terror. <br>
<br>
“Well, well, well. Dylan, long time no see.” The voice was thick with sarcasm that was on a par with Beka at times. All three knew the voice but in their current environment only Rommie could identify it. <br>
<br>
“Cuchulain…?” Questioned Rommie. Slowly they turned to face their captor, Rommie was right – as usual. <br>
<br>
“Fleet Marshall.” <br>
<br>
“Try Lieutenant, all thanks to you. Now its time for some payback.” His voice full of hate, he raised his gauss pistol level with Dylan’s head and pulled the trigger. Nothing happened. The gun wasn’t loaded “Did you really think it was going to be that easy, please, I want to make this last so I can savour every second of your pain. However, you can rest assured, your death will give me the opportunity to regain my former glory and destroy the Kodiak and your Commonwealth at the same time.” <br>
<br>
“Don’t forget Drago’s bones.” <br>
<br>
Cuchulain’s guards looked around at one another, they too had heard the rumours that the mummified remains of the progenitor had been stolen and replaced with a fake, but of course they hadn’t believed it. <br>
<br>
Cuchulain marched Dylan, Rommie and Harper towards the nearest labour camp for interrogation, torture and eventually, their deaths and he was not shy about showing the contentment he felt with the situation. Finally, things would be back to normal and his only true adversary would be dead; however, even he had to admit that without such a person his life as a Nietzschean was pointless. Suddenly, a blinding flash lit the area around the small group and the sounds of weapons fire could be heard atop the inaudible screams of the Nietzscheans as a high pitched shrilling sound filled their ears. Harper recognised that sound instantly, he invented the first shriller upon which the ones his cousin was using were based. The Niets collapsed bringing their hands to cover their ears and subdue the pain the high-pitched frequencies caused them. When the situation calmed down Rommie was the first to regain her vision and was greatly surprised by what she saw. <br>
<br>
“Why Lieutenant, captured by a KLUDGE, that won’t look good on your file will it. How are you Brendan?” <br>
<br>
As she said Kludge, the irony was not lost on Cuchulain even though he was almost unconscious. Harper turned instantly at the sound of his cousin’s name to see Cuchulain lying face down on the ground with Brendan standing above him with his foot firmly pressing down on his back and pointing a force lance at the Nietzscheans head. Cuchulain was not amused. When Dylan finally regained his vision he surveyed the damage, all of Cuchulain’s troops were dead or lay dieing on the ground while all of Brendan’s troops were still standing, even he had to admire the efficiency of the resistance. <br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Chapter 4: Reunited <br>
<br>
Haper hurled himself at Brendan, arms outstretched to take his cousin into the biggest hug in history. As soon as he got within 10 feet, he was stopped by the sound of a rifle being charged. He turned around to see that Brendan’s troops had trained their guns on the intruders; or as they would soon find out, they were known as the traitor from the High Guard who couldn’t keep his word if his life depended on it, the deserter – a coward who couldn’t stay and fight so he ran away (sound like the Neitzscheans they so with to get rid of don’t they) and an AI, nuff said. Fortunately for the trio, one signal from Brendan and his soldiers lowered their weapons. Cautiously Harper walked over to his cousin and hugged him. They were silent for some time but that single hug they said more to the other than words ever made possible. <br>
<br>
With Cuchulain taken prisoner, Brendan led the group to his hideout and his rapidly diminishing army. The Drago Kazov had been going after the resistance much more heavily in Boston since that’s where it started; Kill The Origin, The Rest Will Crumble, that is their motto. Well actually it was The Strong Survive, The Weak Clean Their Boots, but that didn’t do this job justice so they changed it. <br>
<br>
When they approached the resistance's base of operations Brendan went in first followed by his second in command dragging Cuchulain behind him on a LEASH of all things. As Dylan was about to enter the trio heard an uproar from inside the camp, a cry of pain and screams of pleasure sounded almost instantly. It was obvious even to Dylan what was happening, Cuchulain was being tortured and the observing crowds loved every second of his pain. Cuchulain fell to the floor, his face covered in gashes; the blood flowing freely. One of Brendan's men approached him with an oddly shaped piece of wood, long, thin at one end and quite thick at the other. He raised it above his head and brought it down HARD on Cuchulain's back, as he raised what Dylan would later learn was a baseball bat for another swing. Dylan broke free of his guard and he ran forward through the screaming crowds and caught it mid strike. The force and speed of the bat caused him great pain but he held it in, the force with which the bat hit his hand would probably have increased with the microseconds it would have taken for it to make contact with Cuchulain's back. It could have quite easily killed him, no man, not even Cuchulain deserved to be beaten to death, well, almost. <br>
<br>
&quot;That's enough, I came here to keep my promise and cripple the Drago Kazov, not to watch a man beaten to death even IF he may deserve it. Now, you can kill him and live in the knowledge that the Dragan's will hunt you down to extinction until they kill every human on Earth, or, you can help me to destroy their new weapon and eradicate the Dragan presence on Earth and free the planet. This isn't like the last time, I don't have some other battle to fight that's more important, and I'm here to keep the promise made to you and Harper.&quot; <br>
<br>
He started off screaming, but his voice soon calmed to the commanding tone he always used with Tyr of all people. Who would have thought he would be comparing a human to Tyr. <br>
<br>
Brendan looked at the rabble before him, his troops had seen better days; and bigger numbers. Armed with a wide variety of weapons, from gauss pistols and forcelances to knives and sticks. Their limbs had been broken more times than he could remember, their bodies littered with scars and even fresh wounds badly dressed. They didn't stand a chance. He and Dylan had made a plan to attack the local barracks early in the morning when most of the Neitzscheans would still be asleep, when they would have the advantage. <br>
<br>
<br>
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
<br>
Chapter 5: Hope and Fear, lots of Fear <br>
<br>
Harper awoke – soaked in sweat. The lights were low, very low. The only sound he could here – that of his own heartbeat. He had to strain to see his hand in front of his face. As he slowly became accustomed to the darkness his eyes began to focus and adapt. It was still pitch black but he could at least make out he shapes of the objects around him – shapes he knew all too well. He looked around and began to recognise the various consoles and equipment of his home away from home on the Andromeda; he was in medical, and he was alone. He was afraid, very afraid. Harper froze. Instinctively he tried to sit up only to be stopped by blinding pain in his right leg. Fear took control of him at that moment. Terrified, he looked down at his right leg. His vision was blurred from the intensity of the pain but it was good enough for him to see at close range. He stared for mere moments but from what he saw, to Harper, it seemed like hours. What he saw struck terror into his heart. What he saw was the second worse than anything he could ever have imagined happening to him since he left Earth, and being from, Earth he could imagine quite a bit. His leg, or rather, what was left of it, was a complete mess. Covered in blood with parts of the bone exposed; it truly was a horrific sight – below his right knee, nothing of his leg remained, except for a pile of flesh and bone on the floor beside the bed that is. Although he didn’t know it, at that moment fear was his biggest ally. His fear produced massive quantities of adrenaline keeping him conscious which would have made this so much more difficult, but, he was so scared and afraid that his fear overwhelmed the rest of his senses, numbing the pain he would have felt, a pain so great it would have been unbearable. He started screaming and shouting hoping that someone would hear him and come to his rescue. He soon gave up however when it became apparent that no one was coming. The he heard it, a solitary voice somewhere in the darkness, it caused him to wake from his almost sleep. He heard it again and instantly recognised it was Rommie and she was calling to him – this time he listened. <br>
<br>
“We’re all alone now Seamus. They’re all gone, all dead. It’s just you and me now Seamus, you and me against the universe.” <br>
<br>
And then there was only silence. Harper called out to her time and time again until his throat was sore, but she never answered. He was alone again and the silence was killing him. He broke down crying at that moment just like a child who had fallen off of their bike and scrapped their knee crying for mummy to make it all better. But he had fallen off of no bike and scrapped no knee, he cried simply out of fear and of loss, loss of his friends, his family, his home and his love. <br>
<br>
He awoke on the ground in a cold sweat covered in dirt, Rommie ever vigil at his side. His eyes darted around, unsure of where he was. He soon heard Dylan and Brendan talking in the background and everything rapidly came back to him, hitting him with the emotional force of 50-gigatone nuke. He jumped forward and wrapped his arm around Rommie; she could see that he was upset and uneasy, but somehow she saw joy in Harper’s eyes at the very sight of her, Rommie decided there and then that she somehow had to get Harper to talk about that, that nightmare. On the outside Harper showed dozens of emotions at once but inside he was jumping for joy simply because he knew that the people he cared about, and Tyr, were still alive but he was also deeply disturbed by his dream and he knew that Rommie knew that, he was dreading her attempts to get him to talk but he also realised he had seen his worst fear personified, his fear of being alone but he was now much more willing and definitely ready to face it. <br>
<br>
Harper stared at Rommie; the look on her face was one of concern for a friend. He suddenly realised just how late it was, the sky was black, the stars only a faint glimmer through the hole in the roof that served as a chimney and air vent for the campfire situated directly below. Harper looked at his creation, the glow of the campfire beautifully accented her tanned skin, Rommie knew that look, the look as if her were undressing her with his eyes, she made a sound as if clearing her throat. Harper flashed her his patented mischievous grin. Rommie rolled her eyes as if saying ‘yep he’s fine’ but as she stood to walk away Harper grabbed her arm – refusing to let her go. She looked down at her engineer with a questioning gaze. <br>
<br>
“Rommie please, please don’t go, not yet, I really don’t wanna be alone not - not after that…that dream.” <br>
<br>
For the first time since the larvae had become active Rommie saw true fear in Harper’s eyes. She wanted to just curl up with him right there and try to get him to talk about it but she maintained her composure and ‘reluctantly’ sat down. <br>
<br>
“You know Harper, you are a big boy and it was only a dream.” <br>
<br>
“Yeah I know but still.” <br>
<br>
“We’re not leaving yet anyway, the Drago Kazov just sent out a couple of extra patrols and the local base has just been reinforced, Dylan’s plan won’t work now so he and Brendan are formulating a new one.” <br>
<br>
Her speech was simply a statement but her tone was one of understanding and compassion, Harper knew that she wouldn’t leave him like this anyway but what she just said, or rather how she said it just confirmed that for him. He now had hope to guide him. He believed what Rommie had meant, that she would never leave him. Yes he now had to hope to drive him in his life, hope that his fear would never be realised in his lifetime. <br>
<br>
Harper sat up and Rommie sat close beside him, wrapping her arm around her engineer, but she made sure Harper knew it was only a friendly gesture. He’d learned that the hard way the last time and nodded understandingly. There they sat for several minutes. Rommie could feel Harper falling asleep again. Suddenly he broke the peaceful silence. <br>
<br>
“Hey Rommie?” He was half asleep. <br>
<br>
“Yes Harper.” She sighed inwardly; he was almost asleep. <br>
<br>
“Why red?” <br>
<br>
“Huh?” <br>
<br>
“Your hair, why red?” <br>
<br>
“Oh, well I was tired of blue, besides, it goes better with my uniform.” <br>
<br>
“Oh.” <br>
<br>
“Go sleep Harper, I’ll be here all night with you.” With that he fell asleep, then Rommie thought to herself ‘Why did I choose red?’ <br>
<br>
