Chapter 6: Plans and Actions <br>
<br>
Dylan, Harper and Rommie returned to the Andromeda several hours later. Despite all of Harper’s ‘requests’ or, as it’s more commonly known, begging – Brendan refused to come with them or to let Harper stay planet side with him. <br>
<br>
“There’ll be plenty of time for that later Shay.” He kept saying. “Now, get off of my planet.” Was his final response to Harper’s final attempt. Brendan had forgotten just how annoying Harper could be when he wanted to be. <br>
<br>
As soon as they got back to the Andromeda Dylan headed for Command while Harper went to check that the ‘ship was combat ready’ – he really didn’t trust these new High Guard engineers, especially with his supply of Sparky or Rommie, ‘Thank the Divine this is only temporary,’ he thought to himself, ‘I hope.’ Rommie too had decided that she didn’t entirely trust these engineers, well, with herself at least. She quickly began following Harper. That is, until Dylan stopped her and told her to come with him. As the pair walked into Command they finished their conversation. <br>
<br>
“So, you’re clear on plan B?” <br>
<br>
“Dylan, I’m an Android and as Harper is so fond of saying I have a brain the size of a planet.” She said mockingly. “You only have to tell me things once. I’ll be ready, I just hope it doesn’t come down to that.” <br>
<br>
“You and me both Rommie, you and me both.” Dylan walked towards the Captain’s podium and Rommie took up position at the First Officers as Beka assumed her position at the Helm Tyr never moving from Tactical. Despite having a full crew aboard Dylan never really felt the need for a Command Staff, not with Tyr, Rommie and Beka at his side anyway. A few minutes later Harper sauntered into Command muttering under his breath about how trust worthy the new crew was. Despite what the rest of the crew could pick up including Tyr, only Rommie could hear exactly what he was mumbling. Harper hated being proved wrong. <br>
<br>
He walked to the front of the Command Deck and crawled into an access port to do some last system checks before the mission. The second he closed the entry hatch Harper could hear the laughs of Tyr, Dylan, Beka and Rommie, ‘Good thing Trance wasn’t there.’ He thought. ‘Just enjoy it now, we’ll see who has the last laugh.’ He thought resisting the urge to cackle maniacally. He emerged about an hour later less than a hundred metres from Machine Shop 17. <br>
<br>
“Well, while I’m here.” He said to himself before turning towards the Machine Shop. As soon as he entered he made a B line for his secret stash of Sparky, hidden discretely below the Pilot chair of the X-1. <br>
<br>
After he downed a few he reported in to Dylan. <br>
<br>
“Hey Dylan?” He said trusting the Andromeda to open the comm. Line. <br>
<br>
“Yes Mister Harper.” Harper cringed; he hated it when Dylan called him that. <br>
<br>
“The Andromeda is completely Battle Ready, engines, PDL’s, missile launchers, AG systems, everything is, for once, operating at peak efficiency all thanks to yours truly. We’re good to go.” <br>
<br>
“Not quite, there’s one more thing I want you to do first, well, sixty eight more things is actually more like it.” <br>
<br>
Harper’s heart sank, luckily for him Machine Shop 17 had been shut off from the rest of the crew as his private space so no one saw his reaction. He couldn’t believe it, more work, even with a full engineering staff at his disposal Dylan still treated Harper like the only engineer on board. He’d done so much work these days that Harper really did deserve a break however, he couldn’t really say no to Dylan, after all, he was helping him to free his home world. <br>
<br>
“Ok Dylan, what do you need?” <br>
<br>
“Well, you remember the Footprint Magnification Systems you built to help take out the Balance, oh, sorry Rommie.” <br>
<br>
“It’s Ok Dylan, really.” <br>
<br>
“Yeah, as if I could ever forget. I got two scars in that fight.” <br>
<br>
“Any way, so far an FMS is only programmed to project High Guard profiles.” <br>
<br>
“And your point being?” <br>
<br>
“Could you reprogram them to project say, Drago Kazov profiles in stead?” <br>
<br>
“Oh I get it. The old Trojan Horse trick, well, a contemporary version at least. Sure we got enough data in Rommie’s Mainframe, absolutely, give me twenty minutes.” <br>
<br>
“Eh yeah, anyway let me know when your done Dylan out.” Dylan turned to Rommie, looking at Beka and Tyr as he did. <br>
<br>
“Trojan Horse?&quot; She replied with only a blank stare. <br>
<br>
About an hour later Harper walked into Command with a modified FMS in hand. <br>
<br>
“What took you so long boy?” Harper didn’t even look at Tyr. <br>
<br>
“What, I had to set up a production line didn’t I. Rommie’s bots and shops are assembling the systems while the Andromeda’s core AI updates the software of the completed systems. The other 67 will be ready to go within the hour. Harper said proudly. <br>
<br>
“Don’t you think we should test this one first? Perhaps Harper did something wrong.” Harper silently sarcastically mimicked Tyr, and, he was getting very good at it. <br>
<br>
“Harper, enough. As much as I trust you, Tyr’s right, have you tested it?” <br>
<br>
“Not yet, but I’ve got the Maru ready to go, all I have to do is hook up Sally here.” <br>
<br>
“Sally?” Beka questioned. <br>
<br>
“She…Sallywas a girl I grew up with, she lived pretty close to me and we were really good friends, the night the Dragons got my parents, they got her too. And now, she is goinna get her revenge.” <br>
<br>
“Say no more.” <br>
<br>
Harper walked out of Command and headed for the Maru. A couple of minutes later he took her out and activated the FMS. Instantly the Maru transformed into a Drago Kazov Destroyer. <br>
<br>
“Happy now.” Harper’s smug expression appeared on the main screen. <br>
<br>
“Ok, another sixty seven and we’re ready to go. Bring it home Harper.” <br>
<br>
“You got it Boss.” <br>
<br>
